




TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Cobb-Douglas Production Function Once Again: Its History, Its Testing, and Some New Empirical Values
AU  - Douglas, Paul H.
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260489
DO  - 10.1086/260489
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 903
EP  - 915
VL  - 84
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Research into the production function has a long history. Since the first work, in 1928, many studies have tended to support the hypothesis that production processes are well described by a linear homogeneous function with an elasticity of substitution of one between factors. New results are presented here, using 7 years of observations on Australian manufacturing industries during the 1950s and 1960s. In all seven cases, constant returns to scale are very closely approximated, and the coefficient for labor hovers near 0.6. The appropriate coincidence of the estimated coefficients with the shares received strengthens the competitive theory of distribution.
AB  - Research into the production function has a long history. Since the first work, in 1928, many studies have tended to support the hypothesis that production processes are well described by a linear homogeneous function with an elasticity of substitution of one between factors. New results are presented here, using 7 years of observations on Australian manufacturing industries during the 1950s and 1960s. In all seven cases, constant returns to scale are very closely approximated, and the coefficient for labor hovers near 0.6. The appropriate coincidence of the estimated coefficients with the shares received strengthens the competitive theory of distribution.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260489
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260489
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Statistical Theory of Expenditures in Capital Maintenance and Repair
AU  - Bitros, George C.
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260490
DO  - 10.1086/260490
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 917
EP  - 936
VL  - 84
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This study introduces an econometric model to explain the determinants of expenditures in capital maintenance and repair and, indirectly, to question the assumption implicit in most investment studies that such expenditures do not "matter" in the process of capital accumulation. The model is estimated by a consistent-systems technique, with data pertaining to the rolling stock of class-I line-haul railways in the United States from 1944-70. The empirical results indicate that maintenance expenditures are determined by gross additions to and retirements from the rolling stock as well as by the cost of funds and the rate of utilization. Moreover, in light of the uncovered rade-offs between maintenance expenditures and gross investment, the paper concludes that in estimating investment models, a proxy for maintenance expenditures should be included among the independent variables.
AB  - This study introduces an econometric model to explain the determinants of expenditures in capital maintenance and repair and, indirectly, to question the assumption implicit in most investment studies that such expenditures do not "matter" in the process of capital accumulation. The model is estimated by a consistent-systems technique, with data pertaining to the rolling stock of class-I line-haul railways in the United States from 1944-70. The empirical results indicate that maintenance expenditures are determined by gross additions to and retirements from the rolling stock as well as by the cost of funds and the rate of utilization. Moreover, in light of the uncovered rade-offs between maintenance expenditures and gross investment, the paper concludes that in estimating investment models, a proxy for maintenance expenditures should be included among the independent variables.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260490
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260490
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Temporary Layoffs in the Theory of Unemployment
AU  - Feldstein, Martin
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260491
DO  - 10.1086/260491
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 937
EP  - 957
VL  - 84
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The typical worker who is laid off is soon rehired by his original employer. This important and generally unnoticed fact requires a major reevaluation of our current theories of unemployment. This paper develops a theory of temporary layoffs. Specific attention is given to the question of why employment is reduced instead of hours. The role of unemployment insurance and of taxes is examined in detail.
AB  - The typical worker who is laid off is soon rehired by his original employer. This important and generally unnoticed fact requires a major reevaluation of our current theories of unemployment. This paper develops a theory of temporary layoffs. Specific attention is given to the question of why employment is reduced instead of hours. The role of unemployment insurance and of taxes is examined in detail.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260491
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260491
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Interfuel Substitution in Steam Electric Power Generation
AU  - Atkinson, Scott E.
AU  - Halvorsen, Robert
Y1  - 1976/10/01
PY  - 1976
DA  - 1976/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/260492
DO  - 10.1086/260492
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 959
EP  - 978
VL  - 84
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A translog normalized restricted profit function is used to study the characteristics of the production function for electric energy. The results indicate that fuel choice in existing steam electric plants responds to changes in fuel prices. The production function is also tested for separability of fuels from capital and labor, homotheticity, returns to scale, and embodied technical change.
AB  - A translog normalized restricted profit function is used to study the characteristics of the production function for electric energy. The results indicate that fuel choice in existing steam electric plants responds to changes in fuel prices. The production function is also tested for separability of fuels from capital and labor, homotheticity, returns to scale, and embodied technical change.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/260492
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/260492
Y2  - 2024/03/22
